column1: Epic:  Sarbanes Oxley Compliance
column37:
Epic:  Sarbanes Oxley Compliance

Features within this Epic:
 * Map SOX requirements into existing solutions and identify gaps
 * Compliance (ex. Tanium, Axonius) Tool Integration, Report Creation and Workflow generation
 * SIEM Report Creation and Workflow generation

column1: Epic:  Data Center Compliance and Cybersecurity Integration Designs
column37:
PCCompliance03

Data Center Compliance and Cybersecurity Integration Designs for the data center consolidation / private cloud

Key Integration designs For Compliance (New and Brownfield).  Each of the following items will be tracked independently as its own dependency to this Epic.
 * a. Identity Services integration for all components (all OS),
 * b. Asset Management Integration,
 * c. Configuration Management Integration,
 * d. Privileged Access Management (incl. MFA) for all components,
 * e. Key Management Integration,
 * f. SIEM integration,
 * g. Compliance Tools Integration (Axonius and Tanium)
 * h. Network Segmentation (based on BU) Integration Plan (Compliance Regimes, Identity Legacy and RTX segmentation, Hosting and Enforcement)
 * i. Hosting and Micro segmentation based on workload type.  (Use cases and patterns)

column1: No contract in place for Kyndryl with Cyrus1 to order circuits

cross-connects to extend circuits to the room. The target end date to place circuit order is 02/11.
According to the Kyndryl plan, WAN installations are in February and configurations to be done in March . ** If the circuit orders does not happen by 02/11 we may not meet this target date 
According to Brent, this may not be a risk for May DC readiness but is a risk for the Kyndryl requirement for WAN to be up on the network by March.

column1: NET-002: Workstream Owner & Final Decision Maker Identification Needed
column37:
Due to lack of owners for the workstreams listed below, there is a risk related to the delivery of these services (as well as dependent workstreams) .

Owners Needed:
 * Performance Hub Security Zoning Architecture (Default Route, zScaler, Proxy, SOCKS, etc.)
 * DMZ Migrations (Cloud Services)
 * AAG: Administrative Access Gateway
 * Cloud

Owner of workstream vs. Final Decision Maker
 * There has been good BU representation to explain what legacy looked like but a Final Decision Maker for direction for Transition State/Target State (e.g. Business Partner Extranet Connections, etc.) for several of the services is needed.
column270:
04/Feb/22 3:56 PM;Keith.Melanson@rtx.com;2/4 - Week of 1/24 this list was shared with leadership:
 * Performance Hub Security Zoning Architecture (Default Route, zScaler, etc.)
 * DMZ Migrations (Cloud Services)
 * AAG: Administrative Access Gateway
 * Cloud;;;

column1: NET-002: Prioritization / Synergy Maximization Data Gap
column37:
Due to concerns of the gap in data, there is a risk for the teams to prioritize the work to help maximize synergies.  This Risk impacts almost all workstreams as part of Project Optimus as this data is missing for all.

Prioritization / Synergy Maximization
 * Synergy Data
 * Costs and Savings Data
 ** Low Hanging Fruit
 * 3rd Party Contract data – 2022 End Dates (Dan Doyle’s Team)
column270:
04/Feb/22 3:50 PM;Keith.Melanson@rtx.com;Latest known status:
 * Synergy Data - these calculations are with JC Kennedy and will be shared when available.
 * Costs and Savings Data - this data is not currently available to the network team
 ** Low Hanging Fruit
 * 3rd Party Contract data – 2022 End Dates (Dan Doyle’s Team) - Summary of all information requested by Dan was sent to him on 1/14.  Team has followed up on 1/25 with no response.  Sent follow up again on 2/4.;;;

column1: NET-007-DDI support, maintenance, and refresh
column37:
The hRTN Infoblox environment was last refreshed in 2017 (the internal and external deployments are supported by different teams, and were done independently of each other, but are all running the same Trinzic equipment). At the time of the (internal) refresh, Raytheon received a 5 year commitment from Infoblox to provide hardware/software maintenance regardless of End of Life status for 5 years (agreement is attached). For the internal environment, this support contract is renewed by DXC as part of our MSP agreement – for external, the Cyber team has renewed directly with Infoblox. This has been presented multiple times (as far back as 18 months) and placed on hold due to Optimus planning and the RFP.

 

Infoblox has continued to provide support for our environment, with our last yearly maintenance renewal completed on 2/14/2021, set to expire on 2/14/2022. With the latest date for maintenance expiration approaching, Infoblox has informed both DXC and Raytheon that they will not offer an extension of support contracts for any of the outstanding Trinzic appliances, meaning that we will no longer have vendor support after 2/14.

*Risk:*

While Raytheon will continue to have access to the support page as part of the RTX Infoblox contract, the expiration of the maintenance contract will prevent the DNS teams from being able to RMA failed hardware as well as deny access to support tickets for any software failures or potential vulnerability remediations.

*Recommendation:*

Infoblox will be the path forward as we move forward with Optimus. I believe we have already purchased new hardware from Infoblox. Supply chain should engage and request extended support through our transition

column1: Common ATO: Dependency on Global Trade and CAS
column37:
The IRAMP team has a dependency on the following areas for applications to obtain ATO
 * Global Trade: to perform the Global trade assessment on the application
 * App Scanning team : To perform vulnerability scans on the application after it has been migrated
 * Privacy (only applicable if the application is processing PI)

This dependency has been raised to ensure these teams have allocated resources accordingly.
column270:
17/Feb/22 7:52 AM;Camille.Fremed2@rtx.com;Spoke with Global Trade (Carolyn Walsh) on Feb 16, her team is aware and will have their own process for migrating applications.  

Re CAS: Communicated to Mac McDaniel, see his response below 

 

*From:* Mac MCDANIEL <[mac.mcdaniel@raytheon.com|mailto:mac.mcdaniel@raytheon.com]> 
*Sent:* Monday, January 31, 2022 7:27 PM
*To:* Madeline Brewington <[madeline_brewington@raytheon.com|mailto:madeline_brewington@raytheon.com]>
*Cc:* LINDA CIULLA <[Linda.Ciulla@raytheon.com|mailto:Linda.Ciulla@raytheon.com]>; Tim LEAHY <[tim.leahy@raytheon.com|mailto:tim.leahy@raytheon.com]>; TROY COTTLE <[troy.cottle@raytheon.com|mailto:troy.cottle@raytheon.com]>
*Subject:* RE: OPTIMUS PI Capacity Projections for CAS and GT

 

Hi Madeline / Linda,

In regard to our earlier conversation about UTC vulnerability scanning, here is a recap and summary of constraints/assumptions/suggestions.

We understand 368 UTC webapps reside in Boulder, Meridan, Newington, OBB (Office Bld B), but will be migrating to PDC Lewisville and Sterling.  The migration to PDC/Sterling is an effort to consolidate environments and allow accessibility to both RTN/UTC networks. 

In order to support this initiative, you are requesting CAS to provide scanning metrics to understand migration/capacity planning.

*Current Capability:*

We have 5 webapp analysts, 3 of which support RTN apps.  2 analysts have dual access to RTN/UTC networks to support UTC scanning.  Last year CAS performed ~350 webapp scans; ~330 were RTN app scans, and ~30 UTC scans.  The processing time to run a scan takes 1-3 days depending on the complexity of the site and a 1-2 day manual analysis session.  There is a 10 SLA to provide scan results to the customer; however, we typically have results back in 4-5 days.  
(Note: 350 scans is just webapp scanning, we conducted ~2000 scans between hardware and webapp)

 

 

*Assumptions:*

- Once UTC webapps migrate to PDC Lewisville, RTN folks *should* be able to reach the UTC webapps. As legacy RTN users, we have not had any issues reaching the PDC.

 - I am unsure about Sterling accessibility from the legacy RTN network and cannot confirm we can reach UTC webapps until migration is complete

- RTN folks request scans via IBPM; UTC requests via SNOW.  I am assuming UTC webapps will still be performed via SNOW after the migration.  If that is true, CAS has limited UTC scanning agents and only 2 analysts.

- If UTC webapps will be performed via IBPM, that'll allow more analysts/resources to complete scans

 

While we have a pretty seamless process in running RTN webapp scans; taking on 350+ UTC scans may slow down the process.

 

*Constraints:* 

 - We are limited to 4 UTC scanning agents and 2 UTC analysts

- 1 agent can only handle 1 scan at a time

 - Requesting more servers to host scanning agents will take months for approval/install

- The ticketing systems (IBPM/SNOW) have not experienced a flood of requests; I am unsure if those tools can handle 300+ scan requests.

 - Webapp scans are ONLY run upon customer request. This is a manual process and takes time to process.

- Since 350+ UTC apps have never been scanned; initial scans may result in more findings than usual; which may cause ATO delays

- The 10 SLA could be delayed if:

      -  We spend additional time with UTC app owners understanding their environment prior to performing scans

      -  There is an issue with accessing UTC URLs, scan load/influx of tickets, staffing, etc.

*Suggestions:* 

  - It would be helpful to know if UTC has a DEV environment for webapp scanning.  That way, we are not limited to scanning only on weekends for apps in production.

 *Projections:*
- Realistically, CAS could handle an additional 5-10 UTC scan requests per week as resources become available

*Considerations* (if necessary):

  - Approval for overtime pay to get ahead of increased workloads

  Please let me know if you have any questions.

 

 ;;;
